# 2. `mv` Command

## What is `mv`?

`mv` means:

```text
Move
```

The `mv` command has two main purposes:

```text
1. Move a file or directory
2. Rename a file or directory
```

Think about a school notebook.

You can:

```text
Move it from Bag A to Bag B

or

Change its label from Maths to Mathematics
```

The `mv` command does similar work in Linux.

---

## Basic Syntax

```bash
mv [OPTIONS] SOURCE DESTINATION
```

---

# Rename a File

Suppose you have:

```text
old.txt
```

Run:

```bash
mv old.txt new.txt
```

Before:

```text
old.txt
```

After:

```text
new.txt
```

The file has been renamed.

---

# Rename a Directory

```bash
mv old-directory new-directory
```

Example:

```bash
mv logs old-logs
```

Before:

```text
logs/
```

After:

```text
old-logs/
```

---

# Move a File into a Directory

Suppose:

```text
application.log
backup/
```

Run:

```bash
mv application.log backup/
```

Result:

```text
backup/
└── application.log
```

---

# Move Multiple Files

Suppose:

```text
app.log
error.log
access.log
backup/
```

Run:

```bash
mv app.log error.log access.log backup/
```

All three files move into the `backup` directory.

When moving multiple sources, the final argument must be a directory.

---

# Important `mv` Options

## `mv -i` – Interactive Mode

```bash
mv -i app.log backup/
```

If the destination already contains a file with the same name, `mv` asks for confirmation before overwriting.

Example prompt:

```text
mv: overwrite 'backup/app.log'?
```

This is safer when working with important files.

---

## `mv -f` – Force

```bash
mv -f app.log backup/
```

This forces the move operation without normal overwrite prompting.

Use carefully.

Do not use `-f` simply because a command failed. First understand why it failed.

---

## `mv -n` – No Clobber

```bash
mv -n app.log backup/
```

If the destination file already exists, it is not overwritten.

This is useful when you want to avoid accidental replacement.

---

## `mv -v` – Verbose Mode

```bash
mv -v app.log backup/
```

Example:

```text
renamed 'app.log' -> 'backup/app.log'
```

Verbose mode shows what the command is doing.

---

## `mv -u` – Update

```bash
mv -u source.log backup/
```

On GNU systems, this moves the source when it is newer than the destination or when the destination is missing.

Check your system manual before depending on exact update behavior:

```bash
man mv
```

---

# Important `mv` Options Summary

| Option | Purpose                                     |
| ------ | ------------------------------------------- |
| `-i`   | Ask before overwrite                        |
| `-f`   | Force operation                             |
| `-n`   | Do not overwrite existing destination       |
| `-v`   | Show what is being moved                    |
| `-u`   | Move based on source/destination timestamps |

---

# PSA Scenario – Archive an Old Log File

Suppose:

```text
application.log
```

needs to be moved to an archive directory.

First inspect:

```bash
ls -lh application.log
```

Then:

```bash
mv application.log archive/
```

Check:

```bash
ls -lh archive/
```

Important production warning:

Do not move an active application log blindly.

Some applications continue writing to the same open file descriptor even after the filename is moved.

Others may recreate the file.

Log handling should follow the application's logging and log-rotation design.

For production logs, tools such as `logrotate` or application-specific rotation policies are often more appropriate than manual movement.

---

# PSA Scenario – Rename a Configuration File

Suppose you are preparing a controlled configuration change.

A simple lab example:

```bash
cp application.conf application.conf.backup
```

Then edit the original file.

This is often safer than:

```bash
mv application.conf application.conf.backup
```

because moving the original temporarily removes the expected configuration filename.

The correct production procedure depends on the application's change process.

---

# 3. `cp` Command

## What is `cp`?

`cp` means:

```text
Copy
```

It creates a copy of a file or directory.

Think about photocopying a school note.

Original:

```text
Maths Notes
```

After copying:

```text
Original Maths Notes
+
Copy of Maths Notes
```

The original remains available.

---

## Basic Syntax

```bash
cp [OPTIONS] SOURCE DESTINATION
```

---

# Copy a File

```bash
cp source.txt destination.txt
```

Example:

```bash
cp application.conf application.conf.backup
```

Now both files exist:

```text
application.conf
application.conf.backup
```

---

# Copy a File into a Directory

Suppose:

```text
app.log
backup/
```

Run:

```bash
cp app.log backup/
```

Result:

```text
app.log

backup/
└── app.log
```

The original file still exists.

This is the main difference between `cp` and `mv`.

---

# Copy Multiple Files

```bash
cp app.log error.log access.log backup/
```

The destination must be a directory when copying multiple source files.

---

# Copy a Directory

This command normally fails for a directory:

```bash
cp project backup/
```

You need recursive copying:

```bash
cp -r project backup/
```

or:

```bash
cp -R project backup/
```

---

# `cp -r` – Recursive Copy

Suppose:

```text
project/
├── config/
│   └── app.conf
└── logs/
    └── app.log
```

Run:

```bash
cp -r project project-backup
```

Now:

```text
project/
project-backup/
```

both exist.

---

# `cp -i` – Interactive Mode

```bash
cp -i application.conf backup/
```

If the destination file already exists, `cp` asks before overwriting it.

This is useful for reducing accidental replacement.

---

# `cp -f` – Force

```bash
cp -f source.txt destination.txt
```

This forces copying behavior when possible.

Use carefully.

Do not use `-f` as a default habit.

---

# `cp -n` – No Clobber

```bash
cp -n source.txt destination.txt
```

If the destination already exists, GNU `cp` does not overwrite it.

---

# `cp -v` – Verbose Mode

```bash
cp -v app.log backup/
```

Example:

```text
'app.log' -> 'backup/app.log'
```

---

# `cp -p` – Preserve Attributes

```bash
cp -p source.txt destination.txt
```

This preserves selected attributes such as:

* Mode
* Ownership, when permitted
* Timestamps

The exact result can depend on permissions and system behavior.

This can matter when copying operational files where metadata is important.

---

# `cp -a` – Archive Mode

```bash
cp -a source-directory backup-directory
```

On GNU systems, archive mode is designed to copy directory trees while preserving important metadata and links.

It is commonly similar to:

```text
-dR --preserve=all
```

For exact behavior, check:

```bash
man cp
```

This is generally more appropriate than plain `cp -r` when you need a faithful filesystem-level copy.

---

# `cp -u` – Update

```bash
cp -u source.txt backup/
```

On GNU systems, this copies when the source is newer than the destination or when the destination does not exist.

---

# Copy with a New Name

```bash
cp application.log application-copy.log
```

Now:

```text
application.log
application-copy.log
```

both exist.

---

# Important `cp` Options Summary

| Option     | Purpose                                     |
| ---------- | ------------------------------------------- |
| `-r`, `-R` | Copy directories recursively                |
| `-i`       | Ask before overwrite                        |
| `-f`       | Force copying behavior                      |
| `-n`       | Do not overwrite existing destination       |
| `-v`       | Show copied files                           |
| `-p`       | Preserve selected attributes                |
| `-a`       | Archive mode                                |
| `-u`       | Copy based on source/destination timestamps |

---

# `cp` vs `mv`

This is an important interview question.

## `cp`

```bash
cp file.txt backup/
```

Result:

```text
Original location:
file.txt

Backup location:
file.txt
```

The source remains.

---

## `mv`

```bash
mv file.txt backup/
```

Result:

```text
Original location:
File no longer present under the old name

Backup location:
file.txt
```

The source pathname is moved or renamed.

---

# Simple Comparison

| Command | Source Remains?            | Main Purpose   |
| ------- | -------------------------- | -------------- |
| `cp`    | Yes                        | Copy           |
| `mv`    | No under original pathname | Move or rename |

