# 🧑‍💻 PSA Real-Time Scenario 1 – Backup Before Configuration Change

Suppose a change request requires editing:

```text
application.conf
```

First inspect the file:

```bash
ls -l application.conf
```

Create a backup with a timestamp in the filename:

```bash
cp -p application.conf application.conf.bak-20260708
```

Verify:

```bash
ls -l application.conf*
```

Then follow the approved change procedure.

A stronger habit is to use a timestamp that includes time when multiple changes can happen on the same day.

Example:

```bash
cp -p application.conf application.conf.bak-20260708-1530
```

---

# 🧑‍💻 PSA Real-Time Scenario 2 – Count Errors

Suppose a payment issue happened around 2 PM.

A simple example:

```bash
grep "2026-07-08 14:" payment.log | grep -i "error" | wc -l
```

Output:

```text
17
```

Interpretation:

```text
17 log lines matched the filters.
```

Do not automatically report:

```text
17 payment transactions failed.
```

One failed transaction may generate several error lines.

This is a common analytical mistake in production support.

---

# 🧑‍💻 PSA Real-Time Scenario 3 – Move an Incident File

Suppose a diagnostic file has been approved for movement to an incident workspace.

Check:

```bash
ls -lh diagnostic.log
```

Move with verbose output:

```bash
mv -v diagnostic.log /tmp/incident-workspace/
```

Verify:

```bash
ls -lh /tmp/incident-workspace/
```

But remember: `/tmp` is temporary storage and may be cleaned automatically. Do not use it as permanent incident evidence storage.

